and in Appalachian areas, so it's really important for us to

728
00:42:27.044 --> 00:42:30.324
help people be able to get to the care that they need to get the highest quality

729
00:42:30.504 --> 00:42:34.264
care without having to drive three or four hours to Lexington, to Markey Cancer

730
00:42:34.324 --> 00:42:35.304
Center to get

731
00:42:36.124 --> 00:42:39.844
good treatment. So the vision that they set out 20 years ago

732
00:42:39.964 --> 00:42:43.844
was, instead of working on getting people to come

733
00:42:43.944 --> 00:42:47.852
to usLet's work on increasing the quality of the

734
00:42:47.932 --> 00:42:51.912
care that's out in the community. So they started with a capacity building

735
00:42:51.972 --> 00:42:55.512
approach and partnership approach, and it's grown from there.

736
00:42:55.592 --> 00:42:58.192
So we now have 20 independently operated community hospitals.

737
00:42:58.232 --> 00:43:01.212
These are not other locations of UK Healthcare.

738
00:43:01.472 --> 00:43:04.072
These are separate, independent hospitals.

739
00:43:05.592 --> 00:43:09.312
Some systems have that. They have locations all over their state.

740
00:43:09.352 --> 00:43:13.282
That's not what this is. These are separate hospitals, and they pay to be

741
00:43:13.312 --> 00:43:15.772
part of the network. So the goal is to have

742
00:43:16.632 --> 00:43:20.432
increased access to higher quality cancer care close to home, and

743
00:43:20.632 --> 00:43:24.621
higher access to cancer research close to home through a collaboration with

744
00:43:24.632 --> 00:43:25.812
these community hospitals.

745
00:43:26.832 --> 00:43:30.792
And if you look at where these hospitals serve, about

746
00:43:30.832 --> 00:43:34.412
a third of the patients in the state live in the service areas of all of these

747
00:43:34.432 --> 00:43:37.132
hospitals. So it has pretty good coverage of the state.

748
00:43:39.032 --> 00:43:41.232
So they really built the network on

749
00:43:43.192 --> 00:43:45.772
sort of the principle of mutual benefit,

750
00:43:47.012 --> 00:43:47.862
because before,

751
00:43:48.732 --> 00:43:51.472
Markey would go out in the community in different parts of the state and they would

752
00:43:51.512 --> 00:43:55.442
say: "Why are you coming here? This is our area, it's our territory." So it was

753
00:43:55.472 --> 00:43:59.432
seen as competition. So they said, "Let's turn competition into collaboration, and

754
00:43:59.512 --> 00:44:02.872
how can we make mutually beneficial partnerships with all of these hospitals across

755
00:44:02.912 --> 00:44:03.292
the state?"

756
00:44:04.192 --> 00:44:08.172
So a key part of that was a sort of a hybrid cancer care model, where

757
00:44:08.212 --> 00:44:11.702
the goal is to increase the capacity and

758
00:44:11.832 --> 00:44:15.792
infrastructure of the care at the local community hospital so people can get their

759
00:44:15.832 --> 00:44:18.552
care there. But like I said, they're not going to be able to do everything.

760
00:44:18.572 --> 00:44:21.512
They're not going to be able to do CAR T-cell therapy, or they're not going to do

761
00:44:21.532 --> 00:44:25.352
some really advanced robotic lung cancer surgeries and things like that.

762
00:44:26.252 --> 00:44:29.952
So they coordinate with them to facilitate patients coming to

763
00:44:29.992 --> 00:44:33.852
Markey for the specialized things, and then go back home to get their care back in

764
00:44:33.872 --> 00:44:37.592
their community. So that's a really key thing, and so they can

765
00:44:37.672 --> 00:44:39.172
trust Markey to do that.

766
00:44:40.632 --> 00:44:44.302
That is a big value to those local community hospitals.

767
00:44:44.332 --> 00:44:47.212
It helps they're able to use in their marketing, we're part of the Markey Cancer

768
00:44:47.292 --> 00:44:51.122
Network, so it kind of gives them, they can kind of tag along on the prestige of

769
00:44:51.132 --> 00:44:53.212
being associated with an NCI-designated cancer center,

770
00:44:54.132 --> 00:44:57.932
and it improves patient experience, gives them better access to care, and then it

771
00:44:57.992 --> 00:45:01.922
helps us work together on lowering barriers to screening, treatment, and clinical

772
00:45:01.992 --> 00:45:05.852
research. And it really is built on relationships, like everything we do in

773
00:45:05.872 --> 00:45:08.592
community outreach and engagement. This is our clinical outreach.

774
00:45:08.752 --> 00:45:11.972
This is all built on relationships that they started 20 years ago.

775
00:45:12.012 --> 00:45:15.852
And when I first came to Kentucky in 2020, the

776
00:45:15.892 --> 00:45:17.712
medical director of the network set up

777
00:45:18.612 --> 00:45:22.482
Zoom meetings with all of, because this was right after the shutdown, Zoom meetings

778
00:45:22.492 --> 00:45:24.552
with all the CEOs of the hospitals.

779
00:45:24.712 --> 00:45:27.442
And just as we were doing introductions before we even get into talking, every

780
00:45:27.552 --> 00:45:31.341
single one of them said something to the effect of, "We love being

781
00:45:31.432 --> 00:45:34.232
part of Markey Cancer Network. It is so valuable to us.

782
00:45:34.432 --> 00:45:36.852
We get so much out of being part of this network, and

783
00:45:38.332 --> 00:45:39.232
we really

784
00:45:41.132 --> 00:45:44.912
benefit from this partnership, and we're so invested in it." So

785
00:45:45.092 --> 00:45:45.992
I was just blown away

786
00:45:46.892 --> 00:45:50.812
by that, and it's just really impressive, the really trusted relationships

787
00:45:50.832 --> 00:45:53.952
they've built. So there's kind of four things that,

788
00:45:54.792 --> 00:45:58.662
I would say maybe three that primarily bring value to the centers and

789
00:45:58.692 --> 00:46:02.012
why they want to be part of it, and then the fourth one is research, which is sort

790
00:46:02.032 --> 00:46:05.352
of a mutual thing. So one is a quality assurance program.

791
00:46:05.512 --> 00:46:09.312
So the goal is so that every one of the network

792
00:46:09.332 --> 00:46:13.012
hospitals can achieve and maintain Commission on Cancer or CoC

793
00:46:13.052 --> 00:46:16.872
accreditation. And they're sort of high bar standards of high

794
00:46:16.952 --> 00:46:18.772
quality cancer care that they have to meet.

795
00:46:19.232 --> 00:46:22.972
So we have quality coordinators that meet directly with teams on a

796
00:46:23.332 --> 00:46:26.512
regular basis, go through their activities, their reports,

797
00:46:27.492 --> 00:46:31.432
give them templates, give them quality improvement feedback, and they also have

798
00:46:31.472 --> 00:46:33.211
workshops and lunch and learn things.

799
00:46:33.352 --> 00:46:36.832
And we currently have now 18 out of our 20 hospitals are

800
00:46:36.872 --> 00:46:39.312
accredited, and two working towards accreditation.

801
00:46:40.772 --> 00:46:44.692
And they're able to show that joining the network does in fact increase

802
00:46:44.852 --> 00:46:47.852
quality care, because they looked at some data.

803
00:46:48.112 --> 00:46:51.932
The dark blue bar is three years before hospitals joined the network, and

804
00:46:51.972 --> 00:46:55.172
the lighter blue bar is three years after joining the network.

805
00:46:55.612 --> 00:46:59.372
And this is three of the four quality

806
00:46:59.452 --> 00:47:03.222
measures that they looked at for CoC, they had significant increases in those

807
00:47:03.311 --> 00:47:07.242
quality measures. So it did tangibly increase the quality of care at

808
00:47:07.272 --> 00:47:10.612
those hospitals. And there's some additional things I won't go into, but they have

809
00:47:10.672 --> 00:47:14.332
some navigation ambassadors and clinical trial referral ambassadors, which

810
00:47:14.412 --> 00:47:17.432
is training staff and nurses and staff at each

811
00:47:18.332 --> 00:47:20.112
local hospital to promote

812
00:47:21.052 --> 00:47:23.451
referring patients to Markey for clinical trials.

813
00:47:24.092 --> 00:47:26.292
There's other ways, other things we do, and I'll talk about in a second.

814
00:47:26.512 --> 00:47:30.052
But, and they also have a local chapter of AONN, Kentucky Oncology

815
00:47:30.112 --> 00:47:31.972
Navigation Network, that we coordinate for the state.

816
00:47:32.692 --> 00:47:36.542
A really key sort of complement to that quality

817
00:47:36.612 --> 00:47:38.232
program is in the education program.

818
00:47:38.692 --> 00:47:41.972
This is both annual in-person events, like an annual conference, and other

819
00:47:42.092 --> 00:47:45.972
symposia, and also many virtual events during the year where

820
00:47:46.452 --> 00:47:50.312
all of the staff, clinical staff, and non-clinical staff from the different sites

821
00:47:50.372 --> 00:47:50.532
can

822
00:47:51.912 --> 00:47:55.762
have skill building. So it's all about building infrastructure, and capacity, and

823
00:47:55.832 --> 00:47:59.762
skills. And they get feedback on what they want to learn, and

824
00:47:59.792 --> 00:48:01.732
the future topics are guided by that.

825
00:48:01.752 --> 00:48:05.232
But there's tremendous reach over this five-year period here.

826
00:48:05.272 --> 00:48:09.022
They had over almost 5,000 CE credits that they gave out for all these

827
00:48:09.092 --> 00:48:11.312
various learning activities.

828
00:48:12.852 --> 00:48:16.392
The third component is the part I was talking about, the hybrid care model.

829
00:48:16.912 --> 00:48:20.492
How do they do that? They have five nurse liaisons

830
00:48:20.632 --> 00:48:24.532
that personally facilitate every referral in

831
00:48:24.592 --> 00:48:28.452
for the specialized care or special treatment that they need,

832
00:48:28.532 --> 00:48:30.532
and as well as for clinical trials.

833
00:48:31.392 --> 00:48:35.282
So they not only assist the patients with barriers to care and logistics,

834
00:48:35.352 --> 00:48:38.892
but they also do all the care coordination, getting records sent over and stuff

835
00:48:38.912 --> 00:48:41.732
like that. And then facilitate when they're done with the part that they need at

836
00:48:41.772 --> 00:48:45.252
Markey, facilitate them getting back home, and all the information getting back to

837
00:48:45.292 --> 00:48:48.912
the clinician there. And you can see just the increase of

838
00:48:48.952 --> 00:48:51.072
referrals that we've had over the past few years.

839
00:48:51.092 --> 00:48:54.928
I think last year was almost 1,000.Those are

840
00:48:54.968 --> 00:48:58.308
the three things I think that really bring the big value to the

841
00:48:58.788 --> 00:48:59.688
partner hospitals.

842
00:49:00.548 --> 00:49:04.208
And then the fourth area that we work together on is research capacity building,

843
00:49:05.028 --> 00:49:08.828
because one of the COC standards actually is participating in research as an

844
00:49:08.848 --> 00:49:11.648
institution. So six of the sites

845
00:49:12.308 --> 00:49:16.188
actually have their own research infrastructure they were able to build up so

846
00:49:16.208 --> 00:49:18.268
they can conduct clinical trials.

847
00:49:18.308 --> 00:49:21.968
They are actual therapeutic trials they can conduct on-site at those hospitals.

848
00:49:22.508 --> 00:49:26.257
And, they have gone through a really rigorous vetting and onboarding and

849
00:49:26.288 --> 00:49:30.198
training process to be part of these research sites in the network,

850
00:49:31.068 --> 00:49:33.548
and our staff work very closely with them on that.

851
00:49:34.348 --> 00:49:38.108
And then the other sites are not even aspiring to have that

852
00:49:38.168 --> 00:49:39.848
extent of research infrastructure.

853
00:49:39.888 --> 00:49:43.768
They may be smaller hospitals, but they also want to be involved in research

854
00:49:44.128 --> 00:49:48.058
opportunities, so we've devised a way that they can participate in other

855
00:49:48.088 --> 00:49:51.348
types of studies, not the therapeutic trials, but other observational and

856
00:49:51.388 --> 00:49:55.188
non-therapeutic interventions, where they can be part of the research

857
00:49:55.198 --> 00:49:58.108
study, but not be officially engaged in research.

858
00:49:58.148 --> 00:50:01.578
That means our Markey staff are the ones who consent and

859
00:50:01.608 --> 00:50:05.388
enroll the patients and do the intervention procedures with them,

860
00:50:05.948 --> 00:50:06.728
if it's an intervention.

861
00:50:07.788 --> 00:50:10.028
But they work very closely together on that.

862
00:50:10.408 --> 00:50:14.388
They do additional training and networking and professional development topics

863
00:50:14.448 --> 00:50:16.008
as well throughout the year for them.

864
00:50:17.548 --> 00:50:19.228
And this is just a sampling of that.

865
00:50:19.728 --> 00:50:23.368
Since 2016, we've had over 1,400 accruals

866
00:50:23.768 --> 00:50:26.088
that have been enrolled at those sites.

867
00:50:26.148 --> 00:50:29.608
So when they enroll, if they're the six

868
00:50:30.028 --> 00:50:33.928
fully engaged research sites, when they enroll patients, they're their own

869
00:50:33.968 --> 00:50:37.218
accruals. They're not Markey accruals. It's accruals at that hospital.

870
00:50:37.728 --> 00:50:41.168
So they don't go in our data table for CCSG, for example, as accruals.

871
00:50:41.268 --> 00:50:41.548
Interesting.

872
00:50:41.588 --> 00:50:45.368
They're local accruals. So those essentially have been patients who

873
00:50:45.708 --> 00:50:49.068
otherwise would not have had access to research, who were able to participate in

874
00:50:49.108 --> 00:50:53.098
research studies. And then the ones who we do the hybrid

875
00:50:53.168 --> 00:50:53.968
model, where

876
00:50:54.928 --> 00:50:58.668
our staff consent them, they do count on our data table as enrollees,

877
00:50:58.748 --> 00:51:02.508
but they work together. But this is just a couple of last few

878
00:51:02.608 --> 00:51:05.068
years, and it's partial data for 2025.

879
00:51:05.108 --> 00:51:09.068
Sorry, but it just gives you-- To show there's a mixture of investigator-initiated

880
00:51:09.128 --> 00:51:12.988
trials as well as the national NCTN trials as

881
00:51:13.048 --> 00:51:13.288
well.

882
00:51:14.268 --> 00:51:16.928
And here's a breakdown of the types of studies.

883
00:51:17.008 --> 00:51:20.648
So almost two-thirds are treatment interventions, about 30%

884
00:51:20.748 --> 00:51:24.588
diagnostic observational studies, and then the others are other types

885
00:51:24.668 --> 00:51:27.928
of non-therapeutic interventions, health services, primarily

886
00:51:28.248 --> 00:51:28.868
interventions.

887
00:51:29.908 --> 00:51:33.368
So that's kind of what the network does and how we both-- So we

888
00:51:33.768 --> 00:51:37.568
facilitate research happening at the sites and in partnership with Markey and

889
00:51:37.648 --> 00:51:38.068
also

890
00:51:39.348 --> 00:51:42.798
referrals to clinical trials that are only at Markey, that aren't available

891
00:51:42.808 --> 00:51:44.328
at those sites as well.

892
00:51:45.628 --> 00:51:49.248
So the other piece I'm going to talk about is research advocacy program, and that's

893
00:51:49.268 --> 00:51:53.138
something we recently started in 2021, and this is something that

894
00:51:53.168 --> 00:51:56.448
we wanted to have-- Both of these things are about

895
00:51:56.848 --> 00:51:59.428
building infrastructure, talking about sustainability.

896
00:51:59.828 --> 00:52:02.038
In order to sustain something, you have to have infrastructure that can

897
00:52:02.848 --> 00:52:06.638
sustain. So we've been successful with that with the network,

898
00:52:06.928 --> 00:52:10.508
so I wanted to build some new infrastructure to have a consistent

899
00:52:10.608 --> 00:52:14.328
and replicable system and process for us to be

900
00:52:14.408 --> 00:52:18.288
able to support projects involving

901
00:52:18.298 --> 00:52:21.808
patient advocates in their research. So again, these are not research participants.

902
00:52:21.868 --> 00:52:23.208
These are partners in the research.

903
00:52:23.668 --> 00:52:27.288
So we wanted to be able to facilitate them being directly involved as research team

904
00:52:27.328 --> 00:52:31.268
partners, so the patient perspectives and experience can be infused throughout the

