909
00:52:46.868 --> 00:52:50.848
And then caregivers of former patients, again, they also have to be at

910
00:52:50.888 --> 00:52:54.548
least one year out of that treatment experience or passing away.

911
00:52:55.437 --> 00:52:57.717
And then community organizations, a variety of types.

912
00:52:57.788 --> 00:53:00.958
Some are cancer-focused, and there are other community organizations, depending on

913
00:53:00.988 --> 00:53:04.428
the topic. So for each project, we bring together

914
00:53:04.948 --> 00:53:08.378
a mixture of survivors, caregivers, and

915
00:53:08.408 --> 00:53:10.508
organizations that is tailored to the project.

916
00:53:11.208 --> 00:53:15.028
But always looking for diverse backgrounds and experiences, different

917
00:53:15.037 --> 00:53:15.928
parts of the state,

918
00:53:16.988 --> 00:53:19.968
and some are focused on specific cancer sites, for example.

919
00:53:20.028 --> 00:53:22.128
So we kind of customize it to the project.

920
00:53:22.188 --> 00:53:25.908
So we orient the investigators that if they want to be part of this

921
00:53:25.948 --> 00:53:29.848
program, they need to understand that their advocates that are part of the

922
00:53:29.888 --> 00:53:31.688
project are full partners on their project.

923
00:53:32.688 --> 00:53:34.808
They are going to contribute their perspectives and opinions.

924
00:53:35.028 --> 00:53:35.248
We

925
00:53:36.368 --> 00:53:39.948
then facilitate the meetings so that we make sure that's done in a way that

926
00:53:40.768 --> 00:53:44.308
can make people feel comfortable in participating.

927
00:53:45.228 --> 00:53:48.728
And then they can give feedback on very specific parts of the study.

928
00:53:48.808 --> 00:53:52.588
We structure the meeting so that we have very specific things that they can

929
00:53:54.188 --> 00:53:58.058
give feedback on. And then also dissemination as well,

930
00:53:58.188 --> 00:54:01.668
getting results prepared to share back out to the community, looking at

931
00:54:01.708 --> 00:54:05.608
dissemination products, giving feedback on those, and also getting things back

932
00:54:05.628 --> 00:54:06.268
out in the community.

933
00:54:07.188 --> 00:54:10.468
This is just some highlights of the numbers since we started.

934
00:54:10.548 --> 00:54:14.478
We've supported 15 proposals being submitted, about half

935
00:54:14.528 --> 00:54:18.448
and half internal, external. That's how many advocates were proposed to be on

936
00:54:18.488 --> 00:54:20.528
the projects. And the bottom is the type.

937
00:54:20.628 --> 00:54:23.338
What was in FY24, I think that's the current year.

938
00:54:23.768 --> 00:54:27.648
FY26. Currently, at this moment, are supporting

939
00:54:27.688 --> 00:54:30.288
three externally funded projects and six internal.

940
00:54:31.248 --> 00:54:35.108
So about 55, 54 advocates that are actively

941
00:54:35.128 --> 00:54:37.668
involved in projects right now. So it's a lot.

942
00:54:37.688 --> 00:54:41.428
We have a full-time manager who manages the program and facilitates all the

943
00:54:41.448 --> 00:54:43.888
communications with the advocates.

944
00:54:43.928 --> 00:54:46.968
We have a training, an onboarding training,

945
00:54:47.928 --> 00:54:48.368
and then

946
00:54:49.248 --> 00:54:51.448
they also get oriented to each specific project.

947
00:54:51.588 --> 00:54:53.528
We're going to be starting up very soon,

948
00:54:54.648 --> 00:54:58.620
in addition to these sort of... patient advocate committees that are attached to a

949
00:54:58.660 --> 00:55:02.540
project, we're going to be starting a sort of one-time consultation

950
00:55:02.760 --> 00:55:06.700
option, where it may be a clinical trial that's already

951
00:55:06.720 --> 00:55:09.570
in process, and they're just having trouble recruiting, and they don't know what's

